      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The ML surrogate architecture and physics-informed loss function are justified for hemolysis prediction over the nominal CPB operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "A physics-informed neural network (PINN) with a power-law hemolysis damage accumulation loss term was selected. Architecture justification references published PINN hemolysis literature. Hyperparameter sensitivity was assessed on the nominal training distribution; no assessment of model-form adequacy under distribution shift or adversarial input was performed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Input uncertainty characterisation for flow rate, rotational speed, and blood viscosity within the nominal operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Uncertainty in flow rate (±0.05 L/min), rotational speed (±20 RPM), and blood viscosity (±5%) was propagated through the surrogate using Monte Carlo sampling (n=1000) at each of the five nominal operating points. Sensitivity indices confirm flow rate as the dominant input. No characterisation of inputs under distribution shift, degraded sensor accuracy, or novel patient-population haematocrit ranges was performed."
